VI'm going to talk today about energy and climate.
p4
aVAnd that might seem a bit surprising,
p5
aVbecause my full-time work at the foundation
p6
aVis mostly about vaccines and seeds,
p7
aVabout the things that we need to invent and deliver
p8
aVto help the poorest two billion live better lives.
p9
aVBut energy and climate are extremely important to these people;
p10
aVin fact, more important than to anyone else on the planet.
p11
aVThe climate getting worse means that many years, their crops won't grow:
p12
aVthere will be too much rain, not enough rain;
p13
aVthings will change in ways their fragile environment simply can't support.
p14
aVAnd that leads to starvation, it leads to uncertainty, it leads to unrest.
p15
aVSo, the climate changes will be terrible for them.
p16
aa(lp17
VAlso, the price of energy is very important to them.
p18
aVIn fact, if you could pick just one thing
p19
aVto lower the price of to reduce poverty, by far you would pick energy.
p20
aVNow, the price of energy has come down over time.
p21
aVReally advanced civilization is based on advances in energy.
p22
aVThe coal revolution fueled the Industrial Revolution,
p23
aVand, even in the 1900s, we've seen a very rapid decline
p24
aVin the price of electricity,
p25
aVand that's why we have refrigerators, air-conditioning;
p26
aVwe can make modern materials and do so many things.
p27
aVAnd so, we're in a wonderful situation with electricity in the rich world.
p28
aVBut as we make it cheaper \u2014 and let's say,
p29
aVlet's go for making it twice as cheap \u2014
p30
aVwe need to meet a new constraint,
p31
aVand that constraint has to do with CO2.
p32
aa(lp33
VCO2 is warming the planet,
p34
aVand the equation on CO2 is actually a very straightforward one.
p35
aVIf you sum up the CO2 that gets emitted,
p36
aVthat leads to a temperature increase,
p37
aVand that temperature increase leads to some very negative effects:
p38
aVthe effects on the weather; perhaps worse, the indirect effects,
p39
aVin that the natural ecosystems can't adjust to these rapid changes,
p40
aVand so you get ecosystem collapses.
p41
aa(lp42
VNow, the exact amount of how you map from a certain increase of CO2
p43
aVto what temperature will be, and where the positive feedbacks are \u2014
p44
aVthere's some uncertainty there, but not very much.
p45
aVAnd there's certainly uncertainty about how bad those effects will be,
p46
aVbut they will be extremely bad.
p47
aVI asked the top scientists on this several times:
p48
aVDo we really have to get down to near zero?
p49
aVCan't we just cut it in half or a quarter?
p50
aVAnd the answer is, until we get near to zero,
p51
aVthe temperature will continue to rise.
p52
aVAnd so that's a big challenge.
p53
aVIt's very different than saying,
p54
aV"We're a twelve-foot-high truck trying to get under a ten-foot bridge,
p55
aVand we can just sort of squeeze under."
p56
aVThis is something that has to get to zero.
p57
aa(lp58
VNow, we put out a lot of carbon dioxide every year \u2014
p59
aVover 26 billion tons.
p60
aVFor each American, it's about 20 tons.
p61
aVFor people in poor countries, it's less than one ton.
p62
aVIt's an average of about five tons for everyone on the planet.
p63
aVAnd somehow, we have to make changes that will bring that down to zero.
p64
aVIt's been constantly going up.
p65
aVIt's only various economic changes that have even flattened it at all,
p66
aVso we have to go from rapidly rising to falling,
p67
aVand falling all the way to zero.
p68
aa(lp69
VThis equation has four factors, a little bit of multiplication.
p70
aVSo you've got a thing on the left, CO2, that you want to get to zero,
p71
aVand that's going to be based on the number of people,
p72
aVthe services each person is using on average,
p73
aVthe energy, on average, for each service,
p74
aVand the CO2 being put out per unit of energy.
p75
aVSo let's look at each one of these,
p76
aVand see how we can get this down to zero.
p77
aVProbably, one of these numbers is going to have to get pretty near to zero.
p78
aa(lp79
