aa(lp92
VThe second factor is the services we use.
p93
aVThis encompasses everything:
p94
aVthe food we eat, clothing, TV, heating.
p95
aVThese are very good things.
p96
aVGetting rid of poverty means providing these services
p97
aVto almost everyone on the planet.
p98
aVAnd it's a great thing for this number to go up.
p99
aVIn the rich world, perhaps the top one billion,
p100
aVwe probably could cut back and use less,
p101
aVbut every year, this number, on average, is going to go up,
p102
aVand so, overall, that will more than double
p103
aVthe services delivered per person.
p104
aVHere we have a very basic service:
p105
aVDo you have lighting in your house to be able to read your homework?
p106
aVAnd, in fact, these kids don't,
p107
aVso they're going out and reading their schoolwork
p108
aVunder the street lamps.
p109
aa(lp110
VNow, efficiency, "E," the energy for each service \u2014
p111
aVhere, finally we have some good news.
p112
aVWe have something that's not going up.
p113
aVThrough various inventions and new ways of doing lighting,
p114
aVthrough different types of cars, different ways of building buildings \u2014
p115
aVthere are a lot of services
p116
aVwhere you can bring the energy for that service down
p117
aVquite substantially.
p118
aVSome individual services even bring it down by 90 percent.
p119
aVThere are other services, like how we make fertilizer,
p120
aVor how we do air transport,
p121
aVwhere the rooms for improvement are far, far less.
p122
aVAnd so overall, if we're optimistic, we may get a reduction
p123
aVof a factor of three to even, perhaps, a factor of six.
p124
aVBut for these first three factors now,
p125
aVwe've gone from 26 billion to, at best, maybe 13 billion tons,
p126
aVand that just won't cut it.
p127
aa(lp128
VSo let's look at this fourth factor \u2014 this is going to be a key one \u2014
p129
aVand this is the amount of CO2 put out per each unit of energy.
p130
aVSo the question is: Can you actually get that to zero?
p131
aVIf you burn coal, no.
p132
aVIf you burn natural gas, no.
p133
aVAlmost every way we make electricity today,
p134
aVexcept for the emerging renewables and nuclear, puts out CO2.
p135
aVAnd so, what we're going to have to do at a global scale,
p136
aVis create a new system.
p137
aVSo we need energy miracles.
p138
aa(lp139
VNow, when I use the term "miracle," I don't mean something that's impossible.
p140
aVThe microprocessor is a miracle.
p141
aVThe personal computer is a miracle.
p142
aVThe Internet and its services are a miracle.
p143
aVSo the people here have participated in the creation of many miracles.
p144
aVUsually, we don't have a deadline
p145
aVwhere you have to get the miracle by a certain date.
p146
aVUsually, you just kind of stand by, and some come along, some don't.
p147
aVThis is a case where we actually have to drive at full speed
p148
aVand get a miracle in a pretty tight timeline.
