aa(lp182
VLet's look first at burning fossil fuels,
p183
aVeither burning coal or burning natural gas.
p184
aVWhat you need to do there seems like it might be simple, but it's not.
p185
aVAnd that's to take all the CO2,
p186
aVafter you've burned it, going out the flue,
p187
aVpressurize it, create a liquid, put it somewhere,
p188
aVand hope it stays there.
p189
aVNow, we have some pilot things
p190
aVthat do this at the 60 to 80 percent level.
p191
aVBut getting up to that full percentage \u2014 that will be very tricky.
p192
aVAnd agreeing on where these CO2 quantities should be put will be hard,
p193
aVbut the toughest one here is this long-term issue:
p194
aVWho's going to be sure?
p195
aVWho's going to guarantee
p196
aVsomething that is literally billions of times larger
p197
aVthan any type of waste you think of in terms of nuclear or other things?
p198
aVThis is a lot of volume.
p199
aVSo that's a tough one.
